      <hedline>
        <hl1>New York Energy Drain</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>State Sen Eric T Schneiderman letter on Pataki administration's abandonment of energy conservation programs in New York (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Debate on Need for New Power Plants Ignores Conservation'' (news article, Sept. 26) actually understates the damage done by New York State's abandonment of energy conservation programs several years ago.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Debate on Need for New Power Plants Ignores Conservation'' (news article, Sept. 26) actually understates the damage done by New York State's abandonment of energy conservation programs several years ago.</p>
        <p>The Pataki administration's first blow was dismantling the State Energy Department, cutting expenditures on energy-efficiency programs in half and slashing utility-financed  energy conservation programs.</p>
        <p>As if that were not harmful enough, the governor then deregulated the industry, removing all incentives for utilities to promote conservation.</p>
        <p>There is no excuse for this reckless neglect of our precious energy supplies. This summer's price spikes were a wake-up call to our state government: It is time for New York to take the lead in energy conservation.</p>
        <p>ERIC T. SCHNEIDERMAN  State Senator, 30th District  New York, Sept. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
